Chapter 1
Cohren is a proper noun, likely a surname, and does not have a standard translation. It remains "Cohren" in English.
0430 Itania-Time. Cohren hated waking up so early. He hated it especially because he was responsible for waking up everyone else in his squad. Quietly, he got up from his bunk, put on his combat gear, threw on his body armor, and retrieved his belongings from his locker, taking special care with a certain small box. He slung his rifle over his shoulder and hung his helmet on a small hook on his belt. Attached to the hook were all the things he needed, such as his breathing apparatus and his special goggles. After checking his ammunition pouches, he quietly left the barracks. Outside, sludge and ice crunched under his boots.
He took out a lighter from one pocket and a cigarette from the other. He lit it and took a short puff before slightly opening the door. In the past week, he had to come up with quite a few tricks to wake up the men and women accused of being involved. He no longer used the preset wake-up alarm, because it usually didn't work at all and only produced a faint noise from the speakers.
"Wake them?" Cohren turned around and saw train conductor Nemic approaching him.
"yes," answered Cohren.
"What would you like to try this time?"
Before he could answer, the door opened and Harris, Craith, and a few others came toward him already in full uniform.
"Guten Morgen," said Craith.
"Cohren asked, 'What woke you up?'"
"So, first of all, we weren't in the mood to wait and see what you'd come up with today. And secondly, the vanguard, who get up first, get to choose the morning ration," answered one of the men, Ravik. "And you know how bad the food can be."
"Good point, Corporal," said Cohren. He reached in and pressed a switch. A loud, shrill alarm rang out from the barracks. Inside, he heard muffled curses and people running around in confusion.
"Come on, Valerius," said Nemic. "One would think they'd have learned by now to wake up at the same time as you."
" Well, my people from the training camp have learned it," Cohren replied, pointing to Harris, Craith, and Ravik. "However, the platoon and squad leaders also know that they have to stand before their units."
A few seconds later, the rest of the unit emerged. They had everything they needed, from personal belongings to the necessary equipment. Some of the newer recruits looked confused, while others seemed more annoyed.
"Guten Morgen," said Cohren in a good mood.
"With all due respect, sir, why do you have to wake us up so early?" asked a sergeant from the assault troops.
"Cohren said, 'Because the regular alarms are terrible and because Daybreak doesn't sleep.'"
"Crate all your personal belongings," Cohren continued. As a captain and executive officer of the company, it was his responsibility to oversee and support them together with the company commander, Captain Boradin Shaw. "We won't be coming back here. Sergeants and lieutenants, you and your squads have fifteen minutes for the final checks and to pack your daily rations."
The members of the Exodus Company dispersed quickly. They were part of the second Shock Troop Division, second army. Before they were consolidated, they were two companies, Cohort and Dagger. The company was split, and that was the main reason why Cohren felt mixed emotions upon his promotion to lieutenant colonel.
Cohren and Nemic, the leader of the first strike, walked side by side in the glow of the many generator-powered lamps of the forward operations base. Most of the lamps had red-tinted glass to avoid detection by enemy bombers. Daybreak had resorted to Wild Weasel air and ground attacks to counter them.
"Another day and a new task for the Hellhounds," said Nemic with a dry laugh. "Where are they sending us?"
"A forward operating base outside of Ianlos. We'll support the ground assault," Cohren answered, pulling on his cigarette. He gave Craith partial credit for starting to smoke, but a year in the field changes a person, so he said nothing.
"Damn it. Things are getting worse at the front," muttered Nemic. "All the messages say: 'Support the war efforts. Send aid to the Kurgan Front.' What about help for the Howland Front?"
"Amen, brother," said Cohren, and flicked the remains of his cigarette into the mud. "At least we're starting with the first armed column and don't have to run. Captain Shaw should already be here."
"Shaw has offered us a ride?" Nemic asked a little surprised.
"Yes. He's honestly not as bad as I thought. Although not particularly friendly, one can put up with him."
Cohren raised his thumb and index finger to his throat mic and adjusted his backpack in the process. "All units of the Exodus Company will gather at West Parking when they're ready. We'll depart with the first armed convoy at 0500."
He received answers from the squad leaders in rapid succession. Haris, Craith, and Ravik were low-ranking non-commissioned officers when they all came here. The four had been close friends since their return to Earth. Cohren felt as though he had known them forever, although it had been no more than two years. They were squad leaders, though Craith had been leading the second squad for a week now, after the previous leader had been discharged for medical reasons following an ambush by a Daybreak sharpshooter.
On the way to the convoy, Cohren and Nemic spotted a group of about eight Kronos battle tanks and four infantry tanks. Their crews were moving around, ensuring their machines were ready for action. Quickly, Cohren spotted Major Boradin Shaw, who was speaking with the commander of the armed train. As they approached, Shaw looked toward them, and came toward them as always with an expressionless face.
"Private Nemic... Private Valturi..." He said, Cohren was slower, while he looked at Cohren's holstered pistol and then looked up again. "The company is ready, I assume?"
